 as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]},{"name":"Matthias","meanings":["New Testament Greek form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i> (  see  Matthew  ), or rather of an Aramaic derivative. The Latin form of the name is <i>Matthaeus</i>. In English the form <i>Matthias</i> is used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament to distinguish the disciple who was chosen after the treachery of Judas to make up the twelve (Acts 1:23–26) from the evangelist <i>Matthew</i>. However, this distinction is not observed in other languages, where <i>Matthias</i> (or a version of it) is often a learned doublet existing alongside a vernacular derivative."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356698,"age":27,"year":"1572","julianDay":2295221,"description":"William of Orange was recognized as viceroy of Holland, Friesland and Utrecht.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356699,"age":28,"year":"1573","julianDay":2295587,"description":"The siege of Leiden between the rebels and the Spanish. 1574 The dikes were opened allowing a Dutch fleet to sail over the flood waters and rescue Leiden.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathijs Anthonissen was born in 1545, in Middelkoop, South Holland, Netherlands, his father, Anthonis Claessen, was 29 and his mother, Anna Claes Dirczdr, was 26. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Lijsbeth Barentsdochter. He died in 1595, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1545–1595":"1545–1595","1540–1606":"1540–1606","1543–Female":"1543–Surnud","1544–Female":"1544–Surnud","1547–Female":"1547–Surnud","1548–Female":"1548–Surnud","1550–1630":"1550–1630","1565–Female":"1565–Surnud","1591–Male":"1591–Surnud","1593–Female":"1593–Surnud","1595–1642":"1595–1642","1516–1568":"1516–1568","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","about 1591":"umbes 1591","1572":"1572","1550":"1550","1593":"1593","1591":"1591","1547":"15